05308nam a22007935i 9780823281183DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232811837 a10.1515/97808232811832doi  a(DE-B1597)623945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aLA339.N5bF44 2019eb 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a371.01097472231 aFeffer, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBad Faith :bTeachers, Liberalism, and the Origins of McCarthyism /cAndrew Feffer. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b8  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: The Hearings -- t1 The Threshold -- t2 The Stooge Grebanier -- t3 Coudertism -- t4 Vichy’s Lawyer? -- tPART II: Class War -- t5 The Dewey Trial -- t6 The Educational Front -- t7 Far from the Ivory Tower -- tPART III: The Mortal Storm -- t8 Bad Faith -- t9 CCNY -- t10 Flirting with the Right -- t11 Communism on Trial -- t12 Aftermath -- tConclusion: The Coudert Legacy -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations Used in the Endnotes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn late summer 1940, as war spread across Europe and as the nation pulled itself out of the Great Depression, an anticommunist hysteria convulsed New York City. Targeting the city’s municipal colleges and public schools, the New York state legislature’s Rapp-Coudert investigation dragged hundreds of suspects before public and private tribunals to root out a perceived communist conspiracy to hijack the city’s teachers unions, subvert public education, and indoctrinate the nation’s youth. Drawing on the vast archive of Rapp-Coudert records, Bad Faith provides the first full history of this witch-hunt, which lasted from August 1940 to March 1942. Anticipating McCarthyism and making it possible, the episode would have repercussions for decades to come. In recapturing this moment in the history of prewar anticommunism, Bad Faith challenges assumptions about the origins of McCarthyism, the liberal political tradition, and the role of anticommunism in modern American life. With roots in the city’s political culture, Rapp-Coudert enjoyed the support of not only conservatives but also key liberal reformers and intellectuals who, well before the Cold War raised threats to national security, joined in accusing communists of “bad faith” and branded them enemies of American democracy. Exploring fundamental schisms between liberals and communists, Bad Faith uncovers a dark, “countersubversive” side of liberalism, which involved charges of misrepresentation, lying, and deception, and led many liberals to argue that the communist left should be excluded from American educational institutions and political life. This study of the Rapp-Coudert inquisition raises difficult questions about the good faith of the many liberals willing to aid and endorse the emerging Red scare, as they sacrificed principles of open debate and academic freedom in the interest of achieving what they believed would be effective modern government based on bipartisanship and a new and seemingly permanent economic prosperity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAnti-communist movementszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunism and educationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunity collegeszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic schoolszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aEducation. 4aPolitical Science. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  a1940s.  aMcCarthyism.  aNew York City school system